      <hedline>
        <hl1>Actors on Strike: Support From the Many</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Avery Schreiber letter comments on Leslie Saint Bornstein's Sept 29 Op-Ed on problems of getting professional acting job, and her crossing Screen Actors Guild picket line</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It appears that Leslie Saint Bornstein's only hope of getting a professional acting job depends on the destruction of the union she cannot join (Op-Ed, Sept. 29).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It appears that Leslie Saint Bornstein's only hope of getting a professional acting job depends on the destruction of the union she cannot join (Op-Ed, Sept. 29).</p>
        <p>There are actors losing their homes, health coverage and food for their families. Sure, it's impressive to hear the salaries some get, but that enormous wage earner is included in the statistics showing that actors' salaries come to well under 2 percent of advertisers' budgets.</p>
        <p>If Ms. Bornstein wants to support the greed of the producers, so be it.</p>
        <p>AVERY SCHREIBER  Van Nuys, Calif., Oct. 2, 2000</p>
      </block>
